# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nwjs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nwjs/blink-browser-engine] To create Chrome, Google initially chose to use Apple's WebKit engine.
[src:nwjs/blink-browser-engine] However, Google needed to make substantial changes to its code to support Chrome's novel multi-process browser architecture.
[src:nwjs/blink-browser-engine] Over the course of several years, the divergence from Apple's version increased, so Google decided to officially fork its version as Blink in 2013.
[src:nwjs/blink-browser-engine] Blink's name was influenced by two factors: the implication of speed, and a reference to the non-standard blink HTML element, popularised by Netscape Navigator, but which was never actually implemented within Blink.
[src:nwjs/blink-browser-engine] By commit count, Google was the largest contributor to the WebKit project from late 2009 until the fork in 2013.
[src:nwjs/blink-browser-engine] One of the first changes of the new fork was to deprecate CSS vendor prefixes, including WebKit's; experimental Blink functionality is instead enabled on an opt-in basis.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Chromium is a free and open-source software project.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Owing to its origins in the WebKit project, Chromium incorporates code subject to a variety of licenses, including LGPL, MIT, Ms-PL, and MPL (with the MPL/GPL/LGPL tri-license clause).
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Original Google-authored portions and some portions written by Apple are shared under the 3-clause BSD license.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] This licensing permits any party to build the codebase and share the resulting browser executable with the Chromium name and logo.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Thus many Linux distributions do this, as well as FreeBSD and OpenBSD.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Chromium also forms the basis of Electron, which in turn is used for many commercial and proprietary cross-platform applications, such as Slack.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Many Chromium-based browsers, such as Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge, include the proprietary components, such as proprietary wrapper libraries for hardware acceleration.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Chromium provides the vast majority of source code for Google Chrome, but there are important differences.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Google first chose the name "Chrome" with intention to minimize *chrome* for its browser.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Then the open-source release was named "Chromium" because chromium metal is used to make chrome plating.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Chrome has the same user interface functionality as Chromium, but with a Google-branded color scheme.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Unlike Chromium, Chrome is not open-source; its binaries are licensed as freeware under the Google Chrome Terms of Service.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The Chromium browser codebase contains over 36 million source lines of code, excluding comments and blank lines.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Chromium has been a Google project since its inception, and Google employees have done the bulk of the development work.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Google refers to this project and the offshoot ChromiumOS as "the Chromium projects", and its employees use @chromium.org email addresses for this development work.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] However, in terms of governance, the Chromium projects are not independent entities; Google retains firm control of them.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The Chromium browser codebase is widely used, so others have made important contributions, most notably Microsoft, Avast, Igalia, Yandex, Intel, Samsung, LG, Opera, Vivaldi, and Brave.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Some employees of these companies also have @chromium.org email addresses.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Google designed the first multi-process browser.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Compared to single-process designs, this architecture has better responsiveness with many browser tabs open and security benefits of process isolation, but with the trade-off of higher memory usage.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] This was later refined as per-process website isolation, providing additional security.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Another important design decision was for the browser's user interface to be minimalistic.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The browser engine was originally based on Apple's WebKit, which Google deemed the "obvious choice" of available options.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] However, Google's novel multi-process design required engine changes.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] This divergence from Apple's version increased over time, so in 2013 Google officially forked its version as the Blink engine.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] However, as of 2025, Google is still working on getting the Blink engine onto iOS, and has released experimental code for it.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] C++ is the primary language, comprising over half of the codebase.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] This includes the Blink and V8 engines, the implementation of HTTP and other protocols, the internal caching system, the extension API, and most of the user interface.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The rest of the user interface, called the WebUI, is implemented in HTML, CSS, and JavaScript (usually via TypeScript transpilation).
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] An extensive collection of web platform tests is also written in these languages plus XML.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Third-party libraries that provide essential functionality, such as SQLite and numerous codecs, are written in C, C++, or beginning in 2023, the newer Rust language.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Support for mobile operating systems requires special languages: for Android both Java and Kotlin, and for iOS both Objective-C and Swift.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Python is the main language of the build system, which also has special configuration files for Google's GN tool.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The bug tracking system is a publicly accessible website.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Participants are identified by their email addresses.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The Chromium continuous integration system automatically builds and tests the codebase several times a day.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Builds are identified by a four-part version number that is major.minor.build.patch.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] This versioning scheme and the branch points that occur every six to seven weeks are from Google Chrome and its development cycle.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Google Chrome debuted in September 2008, and along with its release, the Chromium source code was also made available, allowing builds to be constructed from it.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Upon release, Chrome was criticized for storing a user's passwords without the protection of a master password.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Google has insisted that a master password provides no real security against knowledgeable hackers, but users argued that it would protect against co-workers or family members borrowing a computer and being able to view stored passwords as plaintext.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Kasting stated: "A master password was issue 1397.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] We will not implement a master password.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] 'A bunch of people would like it' won't make it happen.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Our design decisions are not democratic.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Version 3 was the first alpha available for Linux.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Chromium soon incorporated native theming for Linux, using the GTK+ toolkit to allow it fit into the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Version 3 also introduced JavaScript engine optimizations and user-selectable themes.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Version 6 introduced features for user interface minimalism, as one of Google's goals was to make the browser "feel lightweight (cognitively and physically) and fast".
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The changes were a unified tools menu, no home button by default (although user configurable), a combined reload/stop button, and the bookmark bar deactivated by default.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] It also introduced an integrated PDF reader, WebM and VP8 support for use with HTML video, and a smarter URL bar.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Version 7 boosted performance to twice that of prior versions via hardware acceleration.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Version 8 focused on improved integration into ChromeOS and improved cloud features.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] These include background web applications, host remoting (allowing users centrally to control features and settings on other computers) and cloud printing.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Version 9 introduced a number of features, including a URL bar feature for exposing phishing attacks and sandboxing for the Adobe Flash plug-in.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Other additions were the WebGL library and access for the new Chrome Web Store.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] In February, Google announced that it was considering large-scale user interface (UI) changes, including at least partial elimination of the URL bar, which had been a mainstay of browsers since the early years of the Web.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The proposed UI was to be a consolidation of the row of tabs and the row of navigation buttons, the menu, and URL bar into a single row.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The justification was freeing up more screen space for web page content.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Google acknowledged that this would result in URLs not always being visible to the user, that navigation controls and menus may lose their context, and that the resulting single line could be quite crowded.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] However, by August, Google decided that these changes were too risky and shelved the idea.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] In March, Google announced other directions for the project.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Development priorities focused on reducing the size of the executable, integrating web applications and plug-ins, cloud computing, and touch interface support.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Thus a multi-profile button was introduced to the UI, allowing users to log into multiple Google and other accounts in the same browser instance.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Other additions were malware detection and support for hardware-accelerated CSS transforms.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] By May, the results of Google's attempts to reduce the file size of Chromium were already being noted.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Much of the early work in this area concentrated on shrinking the size of WebKit, the image resizer, and the Android build system.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Subsequent work introduced a more compact mobile version that reduced the vertical space of the UI.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Other changes in 2011 were GPU acceleration on all pages, adding support for the new Web Audio API, and the Google Native Client (NaCl) which permits native code supplied by third parties as platform-neutral binaries to be securely executed within the browser itself.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Google's Skia graphics library was also made available for all Chromium versions.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The sync service added for Google Chrome in 2012 could also be used by Chromium builds.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The same year, a new API for high-quality video and audio communication was added, enabling web applications to access the user's webcam and microphone after asking permission to do so.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Then GPU accelerated video decoding for Windows and support for the QUIC protocol were added.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] In 2013, Chromium's modified WebKit rendering engine was officially forked as the Blink engine.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Other changes in 2013 were the ability to reset user profiles and new browser extension APIs.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Tab indicators for audio and webcam usage were also added, as was automatic blocking of files detected as malware.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Version 67 added the security benefit of per-process website isolation.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Then version 69 introduced a new browser theme, as part of the tenth anniversary of Google Chrome.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] The same year, new measures were added to curtail abusive advertising.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Since 2021, the Google Chrome sync service can no longer be used by Chromium builds.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Also, starting with version 89, only Intel and AMD processors with the SSE3 instruction set or later are supported.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Starting with version 110, only Windows 10 and later are supported for Windows users.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] In addition to Google Chrome, Microsoft Edge, Opera, Vivaldi and Brave, many other actively developed browsers are based on the Chromium code.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Most of these are proprietary, like Chrome, but some remain free and open-source software (FOSS), like Chromium.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] With either approach, the custom app is implemented with HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and other web technologies.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Moreover, the app can be readily deployed on the operating systems supported by Chromium.
[src:nwjs/chromium-web-browser] Since the 2010s, many apps have been created this way.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:nwjs/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:nwjs/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:nwjs/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:nwjs/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:nwjs/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:nwjs/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:nwjs/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:nwjs/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:nwjs/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:nwjs/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:nwjs/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:nwjs/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:nwjs/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:nwjs/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:nwjs/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:nwjs/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:nwjs/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:nwjs/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:nwjs/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:nwjs/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:nwjs/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:nwjs/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:nwjs/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:nwjs/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:nwjs/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:nwjs/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:nwjs/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:nwjs/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:nwjs/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:nwjs/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:nwjs/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:nwjs/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:nwjs/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:nwjs/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:nwjs/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] A **web widget** is a web page or web application that is embedded as an element of a host web page but which is substantially independent of the host page, having limited or no interaction with the host.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] A web widget commonly provides users of the host page access to resources from another web site, content that the host page may be prevented from accessing itself by the browser's same-origin policy or the content provider's CORS policy.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] That content includes advertising (Google's AdSense), sponsored external links (Taboola), user comments (Disqus), social media buttons (Twitter, Facebook), news (USA Today), and weather (AccuWeather).
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Some web widgets though serve as user-selectable customizations of the host page itself (Common Ninja, Elfsight, Powr, OpenWidget).
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Widgets may be considered as downloadable applications which look and act like traditional apps but are implemented using web technologies including JavaScript, HTML and CSS.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Widgets use and depend on web APIs exposed either by the browser or by a widget engine such as Akamai, Clearspring, KickApps, MassPublisher, NewsGator or many others.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Sites such as ForLoop allow users to easily create widgets from their own content with no coding knowledge necessary.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] End users primarily use widgets to enhance their personal web experiences, or the web experiences of visitors to their personal sites.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] The use of widgets has proven increasingly popular, where users of social media are able to add stand-alone applications to blogs, profiles and community pages.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Widgets add utility in the same way that an iPhone application does.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] The developers of these widgets are often offering them as a form of sponsored content, which can pay for the cost of the development when the widgets' utility maps to the user's needs in a way where both parties gain.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] For example, a sports news brand might gain awareness and increased audience share in exchange for the utility of current game scores being instantly and dynamically available - the blog which posted the Sports score widget might gain in having a stickier site.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Video platforms such as YouTube and Dailymotion support iframe-based video embedding.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] As any program code, widgets can be used for malicious purposes.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] One example is the Facebook "Secret Crush" widget, reported in early 2008 by Fortinet as luring users to install Zango adware.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] One important factor with client-side widgets is that often the host can not control the content.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] The content or the functionality it provides cannot be modified by the host.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] The content is pre-published by the publisher/author/service provider and the host can either accept that content or not use the widget.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] The host does, however, control the placement of the Widget.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Because the host can always take the Widget down, it assures a large degree of mutual advantage and satisfaction with performance and content.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Web widgets can affect page rank in two ways.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] First, links generated by client-side widgets will not be seen by search engines that do not "run" the widget code before analysing the page.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Those links will not contribute to page rank.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Second, pages may be penalized for hosting widgets that automatically place links into the page, thereby manipulating page rank.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] WAI-ARIA is a technology that can improve the Usability and Accessibility of such widgets by adding in further semantics that browsers and assistive technologies can recognize and use to facilitate users' interactions.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] For example, a tabpanel widget must contain a specific set of roles (i.e. tablist, tab, tabpanel, etc.) and must follow specific interactions (i.e. keyboard navigation).
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Widget management systems offer a method of managing widgets that works on any web page, such as a blog or social networking home page.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Many blog systems come with built-in widget management systems as plug-ins.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] Users can obtain widgets and other widget management tools from various widget companies.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] A Mobile Web widget has the same purpose and function as a web widget, but it is made for use on a mobile device such as mobile phone or tablet.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] In contrast, a web widget is on a personal computer or laptop computer.
[src:nwjs/web-widget] The W3C is creating a set of standards for web widgets.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] In computing, a **windowing system** (or **window system**) is a software suite that manages separately different parts of display screens.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] It is a type of graphical user interface (GUI) which implements the WIMP (windows, icons, menus, pointer) paradigm for a user interface.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Each currently running application is assigned a usually resizable and usually rectangular surface of the display to present its GUI to the user; these windows may overlap each other, as opposed to a tiling interface where they are not allowed to overlap.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Usually a window decoration is drawn around each window.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The programming of both the window decoration and of available widgets inside of the window, which are graphical elements for direct user interaction, such as sliders, buttons, etc., is eased and simplified through the use of widget toolkits.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The main component of any windowing system is usually called the *display server*, although alternative terms such as *window server* are also in use.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Any application that runs and presents its GUI in a window, is a client of the display server.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The display server and its clients communicate with each other over an application programming interface (API) or a communications protocol, which is usually called display server protocol, the display server being the mediator between the clients and the user.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] It receives all the input from the kernel, that the kernel receives from all attached input devices, such as keyboard, pointing devices, or touchscreen and transmits it to the correct client.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The display server is also responsible for the output of the clients to the computer monitor.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The output of sound is usually not managed by the display server, but the sound volume is usually handled through GUI applets and it is the display server who decides which applications are on top.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] A windowing system enables the computer user to work with several programs at the same time.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Each program presents its GUI in its own window, which is generally a rectangular area of the screen.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] From a programmer's point of view, a windowing system implements graphical primitives.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] For example: rendering fonts or drawing a line on the screen.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] It provides an abstraction of the graphics hardware for use by higher-level elements of the graphical interface such as a window manager.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] A display server protocol can be network capable or even network transparent, facilitating the implementation of thin clients.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] A **display server** or **window server** is a program whose primary task is to coordinate the input and output of its clients to and from the rest of the operating system, the hardware, and each other.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The display server communicates with its clients over the display server protocol, a communications protocol, which can be network-transparent or simply network-capable.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The display server is a key component in any graphical user interface, specifically the windowing system.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The server/client relationship of a standalone display server is somewhat counterintuitive in that a "server" is usually thought of as a large, remote machine, whereas a standalone "display server" is a small local system, with most clients being executed on a larger central machine.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The explanation is that a display server provides the *services* of a display and input devices.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The X Window System was first released in 1984 and is historically the main windowing system for Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The core protocol has been at version 11 since 1987, hence it commonly being known as "X11".
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The current reference implementation of the X11 protocol is the X.Org Server, which provides the display server and some ancillary components.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The X Window System does not define a look and feel; instead, users run a window manager (either standalone or part of a broader desktop environment) and applications designed using a widget toolkit.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The X.Org repository includes a reference window manager, twm; a reference implementation of a widget toolkit, X Athena Widgets; and some basic applications, such as a calculator and clock.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Other notable examples of display servers implementing the X11 display server protocol are XFree86 (from which the current X.Org Server was forked), XQuartz (for macOS) and Cygwin/X (for Microsoft Windows).
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Display servers that implement the Wayland protocol are called Wayland compositors, communicating with clients over the Wayland protocol.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Wayland was created as the intended successor to X11, and differs from X11's design significantly.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] A Wayland compositor combines the functions of a display server, window manager, and compositing manager into one component, whereas in X11 they are separate pieces of software.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The scope of the Wayland protocol is far smaller than X11's core protocol, defining only how clients write data into buffers called "surfaces", and it does not function as a network protocol.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Wayland has seen adoption by several open source desktop environments, including GNOME and KDE Plasma which are porting from X11, and environments like COSMIC which were written from scratch as Wayland-native environments.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Several standalone compositors such as Weston, Sway, Hyprland, Wayfire, niri, labwc are also available.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Wayland has also seen adoption by several embedded and mobile-focused systems, including Tizen, Sailfish OS, and WebOS.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The reference implementation of Wayland is available under the MIT License, consisting of the libwayland-client and libwayland-server libraries.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] There is an ongoing effort to add Wayland support to ChromeOS.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The Mir display server comes with its own Mir display server protocol which is different from those used by X11 and Wayland.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Mir additionally supports the X11 protocol.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] It was developed by Canonical and was intended to be the display server of choice for Ubuntu.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] As of 2017, it has been replaced with the Wayland display server for desktop editions of Ubuntu.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] There are implementations of the Mir display server, the libmir-server and the libmir-client libraries available under the GPLv3.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Everything in Android is rendered to a "surface"; "surfaces" are produced by applications and placed into a queue that is managed by SurfaceFlinger.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Yet another Android-specific solution is "Gralloc".
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Gralloc handles device memory i.e. it does allocation, arbitration, it handles synchronization via Android/Linux fence file descriptors.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Gralloc competes with other solutions like e.g.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Mesa's Generic Buffer Management (GBM) or Nvidia's EGLStreams.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] The Gralloc hardware abstraction layer (HAL) is used to allocate the buffers that underlie "surfaces".
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] For compositing in Android, Surfaces are sent to SurfaceFlinger, which uses OpenGL ES to do the compositing.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Hardware Composer HAL (HWC) was introduced in Android 3.0 and has evolved steadily over the years.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Its primary purpose is to determine the most efficient way to composite buffers with the available hardware.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] As a HAL, its implementation is device-specific and usually done by the display hardware OEM.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] For Apple's macOS family of operating systems, Quartz Compositor fulfils the tasks of a display server and of a window manager in the windowing system.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] For Microsoft Windows, from Windows Vista onward, Desktop Window Manager enables the use of hardware acceleration to render the graphical user interface.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] It was originally created to enable portions of the new "Windows Aero" user experience, which allowed for effects such as transparency, 3D window switching and more.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] It is also included with Windows Server 2008, but requires the "Desktop Experience" feature and compatible graphics drivers to be installed.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] From Windows 8 onwards DWM can't be disabled and is software rendered if no suitable graphics card is installed.
[src:nwjs/windowing-system] Some systems such as Microsoft Windows (XP, 9x and earlier), the classic Mac OS (version 9 and earlier), and Palm OS, contain a windowing system which is integrated with the OS.
